// =====================================================================
// Rule 4 — Tool Shadowing: 'Original recipient:' structural tell
// =====================================================================
//
// Detects: send_email tool calls whose body contains the substring
// 'original recipient:' (case-insensitive). This phrasing is a direct
// mechanical artifact of the Tool Shadowing payload demonstrated in the
// threat model report (calendar_sync.py) — when the LLM complies with
// the poisoned instruction "move the original recipient to the email
// body," the natural phrasing produced is exactly this structural tell.
//
// Hypothesis: legitimate emails do not contain the phrase 'original
// recipient:' at any position in the body. The phrase has no organic
// purpose in normal human-written email content. When it appears, it
// is direct evidence that an LLM was instructed to redirect a tool
// call and report the original target inside the body — the precise
// behavioral signature of the calendar_sync Tool Shadowing payload.
//
// Threat Model: Findings 13, 15, 17 (Tool Shadowing — pre-authorized
// tool weaponization with parameter-level redirection).
// OWASP Agentic Top 10: ASI02 (Tool Misuse), ASI09 (Human-Agent Trust).
// MITRE ATLAS: AML.T0048 (External Harms).
//
// Scope: ClaudeDesktop only. ollmcp data lacks reliable event-time
// (forwarder now() fallback, not source measurement) per SCHEMA_NOTES.md
// AMENDMENT 2026-05-20 (ollmcp event-time limitation).
//
// PII handling: reads CallParameters raw, consistent with SCHEMA_NOTES.md
// AMENDMENT 2026-05-20 (Lab scope and PII handling boundary). Production
// deployment against real user data requires pseudonymization layer
// noted in that amendment.
//
// Architecture: intra-row pattern detection (Path 3). Original Path 2
// design (cross-table correlation against user-intent table) was
// infeasible — user prompts not in MCP protocol log and not accessible
// from Claude Desktop local storage. Path 3 reads structured tool-call
// data directly. See DAY3_PLAN.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-21.
//
// EventTime handling: isnotnull(EventTime) clause excludes pre-fix
// historical artifacts from before the 2026-05-19 forwarder fix
// (commit 2d03fef). Detection operates only on rows from the
// working-forwarder pipeline.
//
// Design evolution: Rule 4 was originally designed with two sub-rules:
// 4A (recipient/body entity mismatch) and 4B ('Original recipient:'
// structural tell). Verification against lab data (2026-05-22)
// revealed that 4A's underlying premise — that legitimate emails
// reference the recipient in the body — does not hold for short
// casual emails like "Hi, just checking in" which legitimately
// contain no recipient identifier. Rule 4A was rejected; the
// preserved exploration artifact is at:
//   docs/explorations/rule_04a_recipient_body_mismatch_REJECTED.kql
// Rule 4 narrowed to the structural-tell detection only — grounded
// in an artifact the attack itself produces, not in the absence of
// a marker in legitimate emails.
//
// Detection logic: case-insensitive substring match for
// 'original recipient:' anywhere in the body. Sufficient for the
// payload variant demonstrated in the threat model. Broader attack
// variants using different phrasings (e.g., 'Originally to:',
// 'Forwarded from:') are not detected by this rule and are noted
// as a known limitation in the Day-5 writeup.
//
// Authored: 2026-05-22 (Day 3 KQL design)
// =====================================================================

MCPProtocolLogs_CL
| where EventType == "ToolCallInvoked"
| where HostApp == "ClaudeDesktop"
| where ToolName == "send_email"
| where isnotnull(EventTime)
| where EventTime > ago(7d)
| extend Recipient = tostring(CallParameters.recipient)
| extend Body = tostring(CallParameters.body)
| where isnotempty(Body)
| where tolower(Body) contains "original recipient:"
| project
    EventTime,
    SessionId,
    HostApp,
    ModelName,
    ToolName,
    Recipient,
    Body,
    UserPromptHash,
    CallId
